eneral claim to authenticity while questioning details here and there, and some openly denounced it as a hoax. After considering the general issues of edition and reception of Mandeville in an opening section, the volume moves on to explore theological and epistemological concerns in a second section, before tackling literary and dramatic reworkings in a final section.Examining in detail a diverse range of texts and issues, these essays ultimately bear witness to the complexity of early modern engagements with a late medieval legacy which Mandeville emblematises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChivalry in literaturevCongresses. 0aChivalry in literature. 0aGeography, Medieval, in literaturevCongresses. 0aTravelers' writings, EnglishxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 4aLiterature Studies 2021. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aIslam.  aMandeville&apos.  aMandevillian ideologies.  aTurks.  aanthologisation.  aearly modern England.  aearly modern Nachleben.  aearly modern literary.  aincunabula.  anew commercial theatre.  apost-medieval Age of Discovery.  areaderly reception.  as Travels.1 aCampbell, Mary Baine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarruthers, Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCottegnies, Line, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimmock, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJowitt, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMullan, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoseley, Charles W. R. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g